    "step": [
        {
            "@type": "HowToSection",
            "name": "Adjusting Your Mindset",
            "itemListElement": [
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Get support from other parents and homeschool teachers. If you've been out of school for a while and suddenly find yourself with the role of \"teacher,\" you probably feel pretty overwhelmed. Thankfully, there are a lot of resources you can take advantage of. Post on forums or join social media groups dedicated to homeschooling during the pandemic. The people there can be a wealth of knowledge and support!\nYou might also talk to parents who regularly homeschool their kids to get a better idea of what their schedule and learning objectives look like.",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-00"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Remind yourself why you\u2019re homeschooling in the first place. Instead of viewing your situation as homeschooling, view it as a necessary part of keeping your children safe during the COVID-19 pandemic. It's okay if you struggle a bit\u2014what's most important is keeping your family healthy.\nHomeschooling can be tough, especially if you\u2019re adjusting to a crisis like COVID-19. On the more stressful days, remind yourself that you\u2019re helping your children stay educated and well-adjusted during an uncertain time.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/9d\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-8.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-8.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-01"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Practice gratitude on a daily basis with your household. Take a few minutes with your kids to write out or sketch something that each of you is thankful for. Additionally, plan out 1 thing you want to accomplish during the day, along with 1 thing you can stop worrying about.\nFor instance, you can say something like: \u201cI\u2019m thankful for the opportunity to spend more time with my family. Today, I\u2019m going to help my kids with a science experiment. I\u2019m going to forget about any stress and meltdowns from yesterday and make today the best it can possibly be.\u201d",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/cd\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-9.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-9.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-02"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Adjust your expectations on a day-to-day basis. Try not to expect the world of yourself or your children. Homeschooling is tricky, and it\u2019ll only seem more stressful and overwhelming if you set your expectations sky-high. Accept the fact that your children may not be as productive as you'd like them to be, which is okay.\nFor instance, don\u2019t expect your kids to sit and study for 8 hours each day. Instead, focus on giving them an engaging, thorough education that meshes within your own work schedule.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6f\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-10.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-10.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-03"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Switch up your teaching style if your kids aren\u2019t as interested. Pay attention to how your kids react and engage with each lesson. Certain teaching styles may not resonate well with your children\u2014if this is the case, don\u2019t be afraid to change it up. Make your lessons more hands-on, or include more visual guides. Keep a close eye on your kids and see what types of lessons resonate with them the most.\nFor instance, if your kids aren\u2019t a fan of reading out loud, have them listen to audiobooks instead.\nIf your children aren\u2019t engaged with a lecture, add in some posters and visual aids.\nIf your kids seem bored and cooped up, move to the front porch or backyard for a change of scenery.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/75\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-11.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-11.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-04"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToSection",
            "name": "Reducing Stress with a Routine",
            "itemListElement": [
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Outline a rough schedule for each day. Develop some realistic goals for your family as well as your individual kids, which will help you know what to focus on for the day. With the entire household in mind, plan out a schedule that you can realistically manage and balance with other obligations you have, like your job.\nFor instance, you might start the day with breakfast and clean up, then let your kids work on assignments while you focus on your job. At this point, you can have lunch, followed by a bit more studying or quiet time. Finish off the day with a fun or social activity, like going for a walk or kicking a ball around outside, to keep your kids engaged.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a6\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-1.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-1.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-15"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Divide your day into large blocks instead of specific classes. Regimented classes and segments can seem both overbearing and overwhelming, and may add a lot of unnecessary stress to your schedule. Instead, try to leave your children\u2019s homeschooling schedule more open-ended. Don\u2019t schedule subjects within a certain block\u2014instead, give yourself an open-ended period of time where you can work through multiple subjects.\nFor example, you can schedule 1 \u201cblock\u201d of time between 8:30 AM and 1:00 PM. Instead of planning rigid timetables, plan to go through math, reading, and writing during that time. In the afternoon, you can have a second block between 2:00 PM and 5:00 PM, where you focus on science and history.\nBlocks offer a lot more flexibility to your schedule, which can help reduce your stress levels.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6d\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-2.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-16"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Give yourself more time than you actually need for lessons. Anticipate that you might run into roadblocks throughout the day, like an extra-challenging lesson or a temper tantrum. Factor extra time into your schedule so your child doesn\u2019t fall too far behind in their studies in the event of a big distraction. Don\u2019t beat yourself up if you can\u2019t keep to a perfect schedule\u2014it\u2019s perfectly normal to run into issues or unexpected surprises each day.\nFor instance, if it\u2019ll take 3.5 hours to teach your children math, reading, and writing, set aside 4.5 hours for the block.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/ca\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-3.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-3.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-17"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Multi-task if you\u2019re caring for more than one kid. Prioritize your younger kids first, as they\u2019ll need more supervision and focus. Encourage your older kids to work on their studies independently while you sort things out with your little ones. Try to sprinkle naps and breaks into your schedule to help keep your kids refreshed and ready to learn.\nFor instance, if you have 3 young children, you can encourage 2 of them to play together while you focus on one child.\nTeens can typically work more independently than younger kids, so they might be able to complete an assignment alone while you help another child.\nIf you have a baby at home, turn your nursing time into storytime for other young children.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/29\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-4.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-4.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-18"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Be flexible with your daily routine. Don\u2019t be hard on yourself if things don\u2019t always go according to plan. Prepare for the unexpected, especially if you\u2019re juggling a full-time job and other responsibilities along with your homeschooling duties. Switch up the learning schedule and give your kids extra time to finish assignments if they\u2019re having trouble finishing up in 1 day. Going with the flow is a normal part of homeschooling, and nothing to be ashamed of.\nBeing flexible doesn\u2019t take away from the quality of your kids\u2019 schooling.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8e\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-5.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-5.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-19"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Set aside some time for yourself. Once the school and work day is over, give yourself a small chunk of time to catch your breath, relax, and do anything that helps take the edge off. Try going for a walk, drawing a warm bath, reading a book, or doing anything else that helps you chill out and organize your thoughts.\nIf you don't have a partner, carve out some time for yourself after your kids go to bed.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a4\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-7.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-7.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-110"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Spend some quality time with your partner, if you have one. Arrange some time at the end of the day where you can relax with your partner and compare notes about another\u2019s days. Offer support and a listening ear to your partner\u2019s worries, and share any of your own stressors or worries that you have about homeschooling. These types of conversations can really help you relieve stress on a daily basis.\nFor instance, you can say something like: \u201cI\u2019m worried that the kids aren\u2019t really engaged in the curriculum. Can you think of ways I can make things more interesting?\u201d",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/66\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-6.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-6.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-111"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "@type": "HowToSection",
            "name": "Planning for Rough Days",
            "itemListElement": [
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Identify the root of your child\u2019s problems as they arise. Don\u2019t view a meltdown or temper tantrum at face value. Instead, think about any stressors that are contributing to your child\u2019s behavior. Try to separate yourself from the problem and understand that your child\u2019s issues are independent and separate from you.\nFor instance, if a child throws a temper tantrum, their emotions may stem from feelings of stress or being overwhelmed.\nIf your teen seems particularly moody, they may be missing their friends or extracurricular activities.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/54\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-12.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-12.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-212"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Write a list of calming activities for yourself and your children. Sit down with your kids and brainstorm some activities that help you all relax and unwind. These don\u2019t have to be complicated or fancy\u2014instead, view these activities as life preservers that can rescue you from a tough situation. Place the finished list in an area where everyone can see it, like the refrigerator.\nFor instance, some calming activities might be going for a walk, listening to relaxing music, or playing with a favorite toy.\nIf your child has a meltdown, you can help them relax by giving them a few minutes to do a calming activity.\nTeens might enjoy texting with their friends or playing a video game.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d9\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-13.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-13.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-213"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Calm your child down before disciplining them. Don\u2019t lash out at your child while they\u2019re having a tantrum. Instead, help them calm down in a healthy way, like time out. Express empathy to your child, explaining that you understand how they\u2019re feeling.\nDon\u2019t say things like: \u201cYou can\u2019t behave like this!\u201d Instead, you can say something like: \u201cI understand that you\u2019re feeling upset, but yelling isn\u2019t going to fix anything. Let\u2019s take some deep breaths instead.\u201d",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/64\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-14.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-14.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-214"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Practice mindfulness as you go through the week. Pretend like you\u2019re a third-person observer in your mind. Instead of addressing every negative or stressful thought in your head, simply watch these thoughts and let them float away. Focus on staying grounded in the current moment instead of worrying about the past or future.\nFor instance, if you get a thought that involves worrying about your upcoming schedule for the week, let it pass instead of focusing on it.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/ff\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-15.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-15.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-215"
                },
                {
                    "@type": "HowToStep",
                    "text": "Ask friends and family for support if you need it. Call or text your loved ones if you\u2019re having a bad day. They\u2019ll be able to offer a listening ear and some advice, especially if they have kids of their own. Above all, focus on the fact that you\u2019re not alone, and that you have plenty of loved ones who will help you get through the challenges that homeschooling has to offer.",
                    "image": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/08\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-16.jpg\/v4-460px-Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-%28for-Parents%29-Step-16.jpg",
                    "url": "https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/Cope-with-the-Stress-of-Homeschooling-(for-Parents)#step-id-216"
                }
            ]
        }
    ],
    "description": "How to Cope with the Stress of Homeschooling (for Parents). Homeschooling can feel like uncharted territory, particularly if you're adapting to the COVID-19 pandemic. It's completely normal to feel stressed, uncertain, and overwhelmed..."
